hands_on_practices.problem:
A binary solution of two organic compounds, denoted as species $A$ and $B$, is analyzed by Fourier-transform infrared (FTIR) spectroscopy using a liquid transmission cell of path length $\ell=1.00\ \mathrm{cm}$. The solvent is transparent in the spectral window of interest and baseline correction has been performed. The mixture exhibits overlapping absorptions in the mid-infrared near the wavenumbers $	ilde{
u}=1650\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}}$ and $	ilde{
u}=1600\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}}$. At $	ilde{
u}=1650\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}}$, the molar absorptivities are $\epsilon_{A}(1650\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}})=150\ \mathrm{L\,mol^{-1}\,cm^{-1}}$ and $\epsilon_{B}(1650\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}})=80\ \mathrm{L\,mol^{-1}\,cm^{-1}}$, and the measured total absorbance of the mixture is $A(1650\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}})=0.40$. At $	ilde{
u}=1600\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}}$, the molar absorptivities are $\epsilon_{A}(1600\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}})=20\ \mathrm{L\,mol^{-1}\,cm^{-1}}$ and $\epsilon_{B}(1600\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}})=140\ \mathrm{L\,mol^{-1}\,cm^{-1}}$, and the measured transmittance is $T(1600\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}})=0.398$.

Assume the Beer–Lambert law applies and that the mixture absorbance at each wavenumber is the sum of the individual contributions of $A$ and $B$. Using the definitions of transmittance and absorbance and the Beer–Lambert relationship, determine the concentrations $c_{A}$ and $c_{B}$ of the two species. Express $c_{A}$ and $c_{B}$ in $\mathrm{mol\,L^{-1}}$ and round each to three significant figures. Provide your final numerical values for $c_{A}$ and $c_{B}$ as a single row matrix.
